###How to fix the Common Vulnerabilities issue of CVE-2019-0215
CVE-2019-0215 is a vulnerability in the Apache HTTP Server that allows an attacker to bypass configured access control restrictions. The vulnerability is caused by a bug in the mod_ssl module when using per-location client certificate verification with TLSv1.3.

To fix the vulnerability, you should upgrade your Apache HTTP Server to a version that is not affected by the vulnerability. You can find a list of affected versions on the Apache Software Foundation website.

The CVE-2019-0215 vulnerability belongs to the OWASP Top 10 Web Application Security Risks category of "A3: Broken Authentication and Session Management". This category includes vulnerabilities that allow attackers to gain unauthorized access to a web application or to hijack an existing session.

Here are some additional steps you can take to protect your Apache HTTP Server from this and other vulnerabilities:

* Keep your Apache HTTP Server software up to date.
* Use a strong password for your Apache HTTP Server account.
* Enable SSL/TLS and configure it properly.
* Use a web application firewall (WAF) to help protect your web application from attacks.
* Monitor your Apache HTTP Server for signs of attack.

By taking these steps, you can help protect your Apache HTTP Server from the CVE-2019-0215 vulnerability and other security threats.
